{
  "Which of the following is the simplest way to conserve energy in a household?": "",
  "Installing a nuclear reactor": "",
  "Turning off lights and appliances when not in use": "",
  "Buying a larger house": "",
  "Using more electronic devices": "",
  "The simplest energy conservation method is reducing unnecessary consumption by turning off lights, electronics, and appliances when they are not actively being used.": "",
  "What does energy efficiency mean?": "",
  "Generating energy from renewable sources only": "",
  "Using more energy to accomplish a task": "",
  "Using less energy to perform the same task or produce the same result": "",
  "Eliminating all energy use in a building": "",
  "Energy efficiency refers to using less energy to accomplish the same work or service, such as an LED bulb producing the same light as an incandescent bulb while consuming far less electricity.": "",
  "Which appliance label in the United States indicates that a product meets strict energy efficiency guidelines?": "",
  "ENERGY STAR": "",
  "UL Listed": "",
  "USDA Organic": "",
  "FDA Approved": "",
  "ENERGY STAR is a U.S. Environmental Protection Agency program that certifies products meeting strict energy efficiency criteria, helping consumers identify appliances that use less energy.": "",
  "How do LED light bulbs compare to traditional incandescent bulbs in terms of energy use?": "",
  "LEDs use more energy but last longer": "",
  "LEDs use about the same amount of energy": "",
  "LEDs use approximately 75-80% less energy for the same light output": "",
  "LEDs use 10% less energy": "",
  "LED bulbs convert a much higher percentage of electricity into light rather than heat, using roughly 75-80% less energy than incandescent bulbs while producing equivalent brightness.": "",
  "What is the primary purpose of building insulation in energy conservation?": "",
  "To block sound from entering the building": "",
  "To make buildings fireproof": "",
  "To reduce heat transfer between the interior and exterior of a building": "",
  "To generate electricity from temperature differences": "",
  "Insulation slows the transfer of heat through walls, roofs, and floors, keeping buildings warmer in winter and cooler in summer, thereby reducing the energy needed for heating and cooling.": "",
  "Which sector of the economy typically consumes the most energy in the United States?": "",
  "Residential": "",
  "Commercial": "",
  "Agricultural": "",
  "Industrial": "",
  "The industrial sector is the largest energy consumer in the United States, using energy for manufacturing, refining, mining, and construction processes.": "",
  "What is cogeneration?": "",
  "The simultaneous production of electricity and useful heat from the same fuel source": "",
  "Generating electricity from two different renewable sources simultaneously": "",
  "Using two generators as backup for each other": "",
  "Converting natural gas into hydrogen fuel": "",
  "Cogeneration, also called combined heat and power (CHP), captures waste heat from electricity generation to use for heating or industrial processes, significantly increasing overall fuel efficiency.": "",
  "How does a programmable thermostat help conserve energy?": "",
  "It generates its own electricity": "",
  "It automatically adjusts heating and cooling based on scheduled times and occupancy": "",
  "It converts heat into electricity": "",
  "It eliminates the need for insulation": "",
  "Programmable thermostats reduce energy waste by automatically lowering heating or cooling when occupants are asleep or away, maintaining comfortable temperatures only when needed.": "",
  "What percentage of energy in a typical incandescent light bulb is lost as heat rather than light?": "",
  "About 25%": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 10%": "",
  "About 90%": "",
  "Traditional incandescent bulbs are extremely inefficient, converting approximately 90% of the electrical energy they consume into heat and only about 10% into visible light.": "",
  "Which transportation method is generally the most energy-efficient for moving freight long distances?": "",
  "Semi-trucks": "",
  "Airplanes": "",
  "Delivery vans": "",
  "Rail": "",
  "Freight rail is the most energy-efficient method for long-distance cargo transport, moving one ton of freight about 480 miles per gallon of fuel, far more efficient than trucking or air transport.": "",
  "What is an R-value in the context of building insulation?": "",
  "The recycling rating of insulation materials": "",
  "A measure of how much heat insulation absorbs": "",
  "A measure of an insulating material's resistance to heat flow": "",
  "The rate at which insulation degrades over time": "",
  "R-value quantifies a material's thermal resistance, or its ability to resist heat flow. Higher R-values indicate better insulating properties and greater energy savings.": "",
  "What is phantom load (also called vampire power)?": "",
  "The energy lost during long-distance electricity transmission": "",
  "Power surges that damage electronic equipment": "",
  "Energy consumed by appliances while they are turned off but still plugged in": "",
  "The hidden energy cost of manufacturing appliances": "",
  "Phantom load is the electricity drawn by devices that are switched off or in standby mode but remain plugged in, such as phone chargers, televisions, and computers, which can account for 5-10% of household electricity use.": "",
  "What is a thermal envelope in building design?": "",
  "A method of storing thermal energy underground": "",
  "A type of energy-efficient heating system": "",
  "A government certificate for energy-efficient buildings": "",
  "The physical barrier between the conditioned interior and the unconditioned exterior of a building": "",
  "The thermal envelope includes all components that separate the heated or cooled interior from the outside environment, including walls, roof, foundation, windows, and doors, and its integrity determines how much energy is needed for climate control.": "",
  "What does CAFE standards stand for in the context of U.S. energy policy?": "",
  "Clean Air and Fuel Efficiency standards": "",
  "Conservation and Fuel Equity standards": "",
  "Corporate Average Fuel Economy standards": "",
  "Carbon and Fuel Emissions standards": "",
  "CAFE stands for Corporate Average Fuel Economy, which are federal regulations that set minimum fuel efficiency standards for the fleet of passenger cars and light trucks sold by each automaker in the United States.": "",
  "What is a green building certification such as LEED?": "",
  "A paint color standard for environmentally friendly buildings": "",
  "A rating system that evaluates buildings for energy efficiency, water use, materials, and indoor environmental quality": "",
  "A government mandate requiring all buildings to use solar panels": "",
  "A construction technique that uses only recycled materials": "",
  "LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) is a globally recognized green building certification system that rates buildings on sustainability criteria including energy efficiency, water conservation, materials selection, and indoor air quality.": "",
  "What is demand-side management?": "",
  "A pricing strategy where utilities charge the same rate at all times": "",
  "The process of building new power plants to meet growing demand": "",
  "A method of storing excess electricity in batteries": "",
  "A utility strategy to modify consumer demand for electricity through incentives and programs": "",
  "Demand-side management encompasses utility programs designed to encourage consumers to modify their electricity usage patterns, such as offering rebates for efficient appliances or time-of-use pricing to shift demand to off-peak hours.": "",
  "What is the rebound effect in energy economics?": "",
  "The tendency for energy prices to return to previous levels after a spike": "",
  "The phenomenon where efficiency gains lead to increased consumption, partially offsetting energy savings": "",
  "The recovery of the energy sector after an economic recession": "",
  "The bounce-back of electricity demand after a power outage": "",
  "The rebound effect occurs when improved energy efficiency lowers the cost of using a service, leading people to use it more, thereby offsetting some or all of the expected energy savings from the efficiency improvement.": "",
  "What is a net-zero energy building?": "",
  "A building that costs nothing to operate": "",
  "A building that produces as much energy as it consumes over the course of a year": "",
  "A building constructed with zero environmental impact": "",
  "A building that uses no electricity at all": "",
  "A net-zero energy building generates as much renewable energy on-site as it consumes annually, typically through a combination of extreme energy efficiency measures and on-site renewable energy production like rooftop solar.": "",
  "What does 'embodied energy' mean?": "",
  "The kinetic energy contained in moving objects": "",
  "The energy that a building generates from its solar panels": "",
  "The total energy consumed throughout the life cycle of a product, from raw material extraction to manufacturing": "",
  "The energy stored in a battery or fuel cell": "",
  "Embodied energy accounts for all the energy used to extract raw materials, manufacture, transport, and assemble a product. Considering embodied energy provides a more complete picture of a product's true energy footprint.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'energy audit'?": "",
  "A test to measure the energy content of different fuels": "",
  "A financial review of an energy company's accounting records": "",
  "A systematic assessment of energy use in a building to identify opportunities for reducing consumption": "",
  "A government inspection of power plant safety": "",
  "An energy audit evaluates how energy is used in a building through inspections, measurements, and analysis, identifying areas where efficiency improvements can reduce consumption and lower costs.": "",
  "A school district spends $2 million annually on electricity for its 15 buildings. An energy audit reveals that upgrading to LED lighting, improving insulation, and installing smart thermostats would cost $3 million but save 40% on energy bills. Should the district invest in these upgrades?": "",
  "No, because LED lights provide inferior lighting for classrooms": "",
  "Yes, but only if they also install solar panels": "",
  "Yes, because the $800,000 annual savings would pay back the investment in less than 4 years": "",
  "No, because the upfront cost is too high for a school district": "",
  "A 40% reduction in a $2 million annual bill saves $800,000 per year. The $3 million investment would be recovered in approximately 3.75 years, after which the savings continue for the life of the upgrades.": "",
  "A manufacturing plant discovers that 60% of the energy from its industrial boilers is lost as waste heat through exhaust stacks. An engineer proposes installing a cogeneration system. How would this improve the plant's energy efficiency?": "",
  "It would eliminate the need for boilers entirely": "",
  "It would reduce the boiler temperature to prevent heat loss": "",
  "It would capture waste heat to generate additional electricity or provide process heating": "",
  "It would convert the waste heat into cooling for the factory": "",
  "A cogeneration system recovers waste heat from electricity generation or industrial processes and puts it to productive use, potentially raising overall fuel efficiency from 30-40% to 70-80%.": "",
  "A family replaces their old car that gets 20 miles per gallon with a new hybrid that gets 50 miles per gallon. They drive 15,000 miles per year. How many gallons of gasoline will they save annually?": "",
  "150 gallons": "",
  "450 gallons": "",
  "750 gallons": "",
  "300 gallons": "",
  "The old car used 15,000/20 = 750 gallons per year. The hybrid uses 15,000/50 = 300 gallons per year. The annual savings is 750 - 300 = 450 gallons of gasoline.": "",
  "A city installs smart meters in all residences and introduces time-of-use pricing, where electricity costs three times more during peak hours (2-7 PM) than off-peak hours. What behavioral change does this pricing strategy aim to encourage?": "",
  "Discouraging all electricity use during daytime hours": "",
  "Motivating residents to install their own power generators": "",
  "Shifting electricity use to off-peak hours to reduce strain on the grid during high-demand periods": "",
  "Encouraging residents to use more electricity overall": "",
  "Time-of-use pricing incentivizes consumers to run dishwashers, laundry machines, and other flexible loads during off-peak hours, flattening the demand curve and reducing the need for expensive, often fossil-fuel-powered peaking plants.": "",
  "An office building manager notices that energy consumption increases by 15% during winter despite the building being well-insulated. A thermal imaging survey reveals significant heat loss around windows and door frames. What is the most cost-effective first step?": "",
  "Install a new HVAC system": "",
  "Add additional insulation to the roof": "",
  "Seal gaps and cracks with weatherstripping and caulking": "",
  "Replace all windows with triple-pane glass": "",
  "Weatherstripping and caulking around windows and doors is one of the most cost-effective energy conservation measures, sealing air leaks that can account for 25-30% of heating energy loss in a building.": "",
  "A developing country is experiencing rapid economic growth and its electricity demand is projected to double in 10 years. Rather than building new power plants, the government considers investing heavily in energy efficiency programs. Why might this approach be more economical?": "",
  "Because energy efficiency eliminates the need for electricity entirely": "",
  "Because reducing demand through efficiency is often cheaper per kilowatt-hour than building new generation capacity": "",
  "Because energy efficiency programs never cost anything to implement": "",
  "Because new power plants are illegal to build in developing countries": "",
  "Energy efficiency is often called the 'first fuel' because it is typically cheaper to save a unit of energy through efficiency improvements than to generate a new unit, avoiding the massive capital costs of new power plants and transmission infrastructure.": "",
  "A homeowner installs a high-efficiency furnace that is 95% efficient, replacing an old furnace that was 60% efficient. If the home requires 100 million BTUs of heat per winter, how much less fuel energy will the new furnace need compared to the old one?": "",
  "About 95 million BTUs less": "",
  "About 5 million BTUs less": "",
  "About 35 million BTUs less": "",
  "About 62 million BTUs less": "",
  "The old furnace needed 100M/0.60 = 167M BTUs of fuel. The new furnace needs 100M/0.95 = 105M BTUs. The difference is approximately 62 million BTUs less fuel energy required per winter.": "",
  "A university campus has 50 buildings and wants to achieve carbon neutrality by 2035. An energy audit shows that 45% of energy is used for heating, 30% for electricity, and 25% for transportation. Which combination of strategies would most effectively reduce overall campus energy consumption?": "",
  "Plant trees around all buildings to provide shade": "",
  "Only install solar panels on building rooftops": "",
  "Focus exclusively on switching to electric vehicles": "",
  "Retrofit buildings with better insulation, install ground-source heat pumps, upgrade to LED lighting, and electrify the vehicle fleet": "",
  "A comprehensive approach addressing all three major energy uses is most effective. Building retrofits reduce heating loads (45% of energy), lighting upgrades cut electricity use (30%), and fleet electrification addresses transportation (25%).": "",
  "A country introduces strict appliance efficiency standards, requiring all new refrigerators to use 50% less electricity than models sold 10 years ago. Critics argue this will raise appliance prices. What is the typical long-term economic outcome of such standards?": "",
  "Manufacturers go bankrupt because consumers refuse to buy efficient appliances": "",
  "Appliance prices permanently double and consumers lose money overall": "",
  "Energy consumption increases because people buy more appliances": "",
  "The initial price increase is offset by lower electricity bills over the appliance's lifetime, resulting in net savings": "",
  "Historical evidence shows that appliance efficiency standards lead to modest initial price increases that are more than recovered through lifetime energy savings. U.S. refrigerator standards reduced energy use by 75% while average prices actually decreased.": "",
  "A large data center consumes 50 megawatts of electricity, with 40% used for cooling the servers. The facility manager is considering relocating the data center to a Nordic country with cold ambient temperatures. How would this relocation improve energy efficiency?": "",
  "It would not improve efficiency because servers use the same energy everywhere": "",
  "Cold ambient air can be used for free cooling, dramatically reducing the 20 megawatts currently spent on mechanical cooling": "",
  "Nordic countries have cheaper electricity, but energy efficiency would remain the same": "",
  "The servers would run faster in cold temperatures, using more energy": "",
  "In cold climates, data centers can use outside air for free cooling instead of energy-intensive mechanical chillers. Since 40% of the facility's 50 MW (20 MW) goes to cooling, free cooling could save most of that energy.": ""
